BEGIN NOW "it is better to make doubt of those things which are secret, than to strive about those things that are uncertain." END
BEGIN NOW There be many words in the Scriptures, which be never found there but once, (having neither brother or neighbor, as the Hebrews speak) so that we cannot be holpen by conference of places. END
BEGIN NOW Again, there be many rare names of certain birds, beasts and precious stones, etc. END
BEGIN NOW concerning the Hebrews themselves are so divided among themselves for judgment, that they may seem to have defined this or that, rather because they would say something, than because they were sure of that which they said, as S. Jerome somewhere saith of the Septuagint. END
BEGIN NOW Now in such a case, doth not a margin do well to admonish the Reader to seek further, and not to conclude or dogmatize upon this or that peremptorily? END
BEGIN NOW For as it is a fault of incredulity, to doubt of those things that are evident: so to determine of such things as the Spirit of God hath left (even in the judgment of the judicious) questionable, can be no less than presumption. END
